GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 814
Short Title: Power Infrastructure Resiliency & Eff.(PIRE). (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives K. Hall, Zenger, Gable, and T. Brown (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Energy and Public Utilities, if favorable, Commerce and Economic Development,
if favorable, Rules, Calendar, and Operations of the House
April 8, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT PROMOTING THE USE OF ADVANCED CONDUCTORS AND GRID
3 ENHANCING TECHNOLOGIES.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5 SECTION 1. G.S. 62-2 reads as rewritten:
6 "§ 62-2. Declaration of policy.
7 (a) Upon investigation, it has been determined that the rates, services and operations of
8 public utilities as defined herein, are affected with the public interest and that the availability of
9 an adequate and reliable supply of electric power and natural gas to the people, economy and
10 government of North Carolina is a matter of public policy. It is hereby declared to be the policy
11 of the State of North Carolina:
12 …
13 (11) To promote, to the maximum extent practicable, the deployment of advanced
14 conductors and grid enhancing technologies to transport the regulated public
15 utilities' electric energy supply in the most efficient means practicable. To that
16 end, to require transmission planning to be coordinated with energy planning
17 and the fixing of rates in a manner to result in the least cost mix of generation
18 and transmission capital expenditure that is achievable.
19 …."
20 SECTION 2. G.S. 62-100 reads as rewritten:
21 "Article 5A.
22 "Siting of Transmission Lines.
23 "§ 62-100. Definitions.
24 As used in this Article:
25 (1) The term "begin to construct" includes Advanced conductors. – Any
26 conductor that has a direct current electrical resistance at least ten percent
27 (10%) lower than aluminum conductor steel reinforced lines of a similar
28 diameter.
29 (1a) Begin to construct. – Includes any clearing of land, excavation, or other action
30 that would adversely affect the natural environment of the route of a
31 transmission line; but that term does not include land surveys, boring to
32 ascertain geological conditions, or similar preliminary work undertaken to
33 determine the suitability of proposed routes for a transmission line that results
34 in temporary changes to the land.
*H814-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) The word "county" means any County. – Any one of the counties listed in
2 G.S. 153A-10.
3 (2a) Grid enhancing technology. – Any hardware or software technology that
4 enhances the performance or improves the efficiency of a transmission
5 system. Includes energy storage as a transmission asset, dynamic line ratings,
6 advanced power flow control technology, topology optimization, and flexible
7 alternating current transmission systems.
8 (3) The word "land" means any Land. – Any real estate or any estate or interest
9 in real estate, including water and riparian rights, regardless of the use to
10 which it is devoted.
11 (4) The word "lines" means distribution Lines. – Distribution lines and
12 transmission lines collectively.
13 (5) The word "municipality" means any Municipality. – Any incorporated
14 community, whether designated as a city, town, or village and any area over
15 which it exercises any of the powers granted by Chapter 160D of the General
16 Statutes.
17 (6) The term "public utility" means any Public utility. – Any of the following:
18 a. A public utility, as defined in G.S. 62-3(23).
19 b. An electric membership corporation.
20 c. A joint municipal power agency.
21 d. A city or county that is engaged in producing, generating, transmitting,
22 delivering, or furnishing electricity for private or public use.
23 (7) The term "transmission line" means an Transmission line. – An electric line
24 designed with a capacity of at least 161 kilovolts."
25 SECTION 3. G.S. 62-101 reads as rewritten:
26 "§ 62-101. Certificate to construct transmission line.
27 …
28 (c) A certificate is not required for construction of any of the following lines:
29 (1) A line designed to carry less than 161 kilovolts;kilovolts.
30 (2) The replacement or expansion of an existing line with a similar line in
31 substantially the same location, or the rebuilding, upgrading, modifying,
32 modernizing, or reconstructing of an existing line for the purpose of increasing
33 capacity by no greater than seventy-five percent (75%) of the existing lines or
34 widening an existing right-of-way;right-of-way.
35 (2a) The upgrading, modifying, modernizing, or reconstructing of an existing line
36 for the purpose of increasing capacity solely through the deployment of
37 advanced conductors and/or grid enhancing technologies for any of the
38 following purposes:
39 a. Increasing transmission capacity.
40 b. Increasing transmission efficiency.
41 c. Reducing system congestion.
42 d. Reducing curtailment of energy generation resources.
43 e. Increasing reliability.
44 f. Increasing resiliency.
45 g. Increasing capacity to connect new generation resources.
46 (3) A transmission line over which the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission
47 has licensing jurisdiction, if the Commission determines that agency has
48 conducted a proceeding substantially equivalent to the proceeding required by
49 this Article;Article.
50 (4) Any transmission line for which, before March 6, 1989, a public utility or
51 other person has surveyed a proposed route and, based on that route, has
