1 acquired rights-of-way for it by voluntary conveyances or has filed
2 condemnation proceedings for acquiring those rights-of-way which, together,
3 involve twenty-five percent (25%) or more of the total length of the proposed
4 route;route.
5 (5) An electric membership corporation owned transmission line for which the
6 construction or upgrading has had a proceeding conducted which the
7 Commission determines is substantially equivalent to the proceeding required
8 by this Article;Article.
9 (6) Any line owned by a municipality to be constructed wholly within the
10 corporate limits of that municipality.
11 …."
12 SECTION 4. G.S. 62-102 reads as rewritten:
13 "§ 62-102. Application for certificate.
14 (a) An applicant for the certificate described in G.S. 62-101 shall file an application with
15 the Commission containing all of the following information:
16 (1) The reasons the transmission line is needed;needed.
17 (2) A description of the proposed location of the transmission line;line.
18 (3) A description of the proposed transmission line;line.
19 (3a) Descriptions of any advanced reconductoring and/or grid enhancing
20 technologies to be utilized and a summary of the costs and benefits, including,
21 but not limited to, all of the following:
22 a. Increasing transmission capacity.
23 b. Increasing transmission efficiency.
24 c. Reducing system congestion.
25 d. Reducing curtailment of energy generation resources.
26 e. Increasing reliability.
27 f. Increasing resiliency.
28 g. Increasing capacity to connect new generation resources.
29 (3b) A description of any alternatives, including alternative configurations of
30 advanced reconductoring and/or grid enhancing technologies, evaluated but
31 not selected for the proposed transmission line and a summary of the costs and
32 benefits of these alternatives.
33 (4) An environmental report setting forth:forth all of the following:
34 a. The environmental impact of the proposed action;action.
35 b. Any proposed mitigating measures that may minimize the
36 environmental impact; andimpact.
37 c. Alternatives to the proposed action.
38 (5) A list of all necessary approvals that the applicant must obtain before it may
39 begin to construct the transmission line; andline.
40 (6) Any other information the Commission requires.
41 …."
42 SECTION 5. G.S. 62-110.9 reads as rewritten:
43 "§ 62-110.9. Requirements concerning reductions in emissions of carbon dioxide from
44 electric public utilities.
45 The Utilities Commission shall take all reasonable steps to achieve a seventy percent (70%)
46 reduction in emissions of carbon dioxide (CO2) emitted in the State from electric generating
47 facilities owned or operated by electric public utilities from 2005 levels by the year 2030 and
48 carbon neutrality by the year 2050. For purposes of this section, (i) "electric public utility" means
49 any electric public utility as defined in G.S. 62-3(23) serving at least 150,000 North Carolina
50 retail jurisdictional customers as of January 1, 2021, and (ii) "carbon neutrality" means for every
51 ton of CO2 emitted in the State from electric generating facilities owned or operated by or on
House Bill 814-First Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 behalf of electric public utilities, an equivalent amount of CO2 is reduced, removed, prevented,
2 or offset, provided that the offsets are verifiable and do not exceed five percent (5%) of the
3 authorized reduction goal. In achieving the authorized carbon reduction goals, the Utilities
4 Commission shall:
5 …
6 (3) Ensure any generation and resource changes maintain or improve upon the
7 adequacy and reliability of the existing grid. The Carbon Plan shall require the
8 electric public utility to produce a report demonstrating it evaluated a range of
9 cost-effective transmission and distribution solutions, including advanced
10 reconductoring and/or grid enhancing technologies as defined in G.S. 62-100,
11 joint projects with neighboring and other regional utilities, other upgrades to
12 existing facilities, and other best practices. The report should include
13 descriptions of any advanced reconductoring and/or grid enhancing
14 technologies to be utilized and a summary of costs and benefits, and a
15 description of any alternatives, including alternative configurations of
16 advanced conductoring and/or grid enhancing technologies, evaluated but not
17 selected in the Carbon Plan and a summary of the costs and benefits of these
18 alternatives. The electric public utility shall also include all of the following
19 in the report:
20 a. Updates to the utility's transmission plan under the utility's open access
21 transmission tariff pursuant to the federal jurisdictional planning
22 process. In this report, the utility shall, when applicable, describe
23 planned transmission improvements specific to siting of new resources
24 expected to impact interconnection constraints or other operations of
25 the systems. The utility shall also describe how it evaluated alternate
26 transmission technologies when developing solutions for identified
27 transmission needs for interconnecting new generation resources.
28 b. A description of how transmission factored into the utility's evaluation
29 of the range of future scenarios included in the 15-year time period of
30 the utility's resource plan, including the retirement of the utility's coal
31 generation.
32 c. A discussion of transmission considerations for facilities included in
33 the utility's preferred resource plan for which there are particular sites
34 specified.
35 …."
36 SECTION 6. This act is effective when it becomes law.
